    "body": "How would one do what he is asking? How would one detect which network is active (or will be active) when `hardhat.config.ts` is imported?\r\n\r\nExample use-case: I want to print debug information about the current network config while I'm assembling it.\r\n\r\n```javascript\r\nmodule.exports = {\r\n\r\n  ...\r\n\r\n  networks: {\r\n\r\n     mumbai: createConfig(\"mumbai\", { debug: isActive() },\r\n\r\n  }\r\n\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nI ended up doing `extendEnvironment`, which is \"ok\" but not \"ideal\" because it is after the config has been constructed, while I am looking for a way to do so while still constructing (prior to executing).\r\n\r\n```javascript\r\nextendEnvironment(async (hre) => {\r\n    // @ts-ignore\r\n    console.trace(`hardhat.networks.${hre.network.name}`, HARDHAT_CONFIG.networks[hre.network.name]);\r\n})\r\n```",
